SIMPLE: astrict
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Astrict
<hw>As*trict"</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Astricted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Astricting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>astrictus</ets>, p.
p. of <ets>astringere</ets>. See <er>Astringe</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To bind up; to confine; to constrict; to contract.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The solid parts were to be relaxed or <qex>astricted</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To bind; to constrain; to restrict; to limit.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The mind is <qex>astricted</qex> to certain necessary modes or
forms of thought.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Scots Law)</fld> <def>To restrict the tenure of;
<as>as, to <ex>astrict</ex> lands</as>. See <er>Astriction</er>,
4.</def> <rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Astrict</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Astrict
<hw>As*trict"</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Concise; contracted.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Weever.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Astriction</ent>⟦br⟧
